<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102268927288347></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102268927288347><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=102268927288347>RE: Quick Thought...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=102268927288347#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=61489><span id=Scholar>Kamlatir, Eater of Souls</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>60 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, May 29th 12:31 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well I just finished reading this huge thread and I feel I want to add my views on some things here. I am a level 60 shadowknight, raid buffed I'm at 4800 hp's and 1300ac, my guild does the planes of course and I've done both regular ToV and NtoV. I play on a (Rathe)r old server and my guild is in no way &quot;uber&quot; or part of the top guilds there. I look at this from the end results point of view since that is the capacity it will affect me in. Everyone and their mother seems to have an sk twink, I have always played my sk as my main character and will continue to do so.<br><br>The original poster brings up a few suggestions to increase the want for sk's in exp groups. By lowering the ratio on sk weapons, increasing the hp return for our sta and giving us higher level necro spells earlier on you would produce a tank that can take close to the same amount of beating as a warrior but focuses more on spells to deal damage then melee and that groups would find more desirable.<br><br>First off I disagree with the preposition on which this whole change would be based. I used to feel that there were less demand for shadowknights in groups but through experience I've changed my view on this gradually. Intelligent and experienced players are aware of a few basic facts: sk's don't deal the same amount of damage as a warrior. You can think that with spells you can both equate and surpass a warrior damage wise but this is simply not true. The point of an exp group is for mobs to die fast. At 60 I have access to Asystole, a 690dmg dot over 60 seconds, stack this with Boil Blood (504 over 70 or 80 secs) and you'll achieve 500 to 600 dot damage before the mob is dead. This isn't even close to what the warriors outdamage you with. Admittedly, among my friends I count two of the best equipped warriors on the server but I believe I'm not lagging that far behind them quality-of-equipment-wise with my Darkmetal Falchion (27dmg, 29del), I'd say I'm a step below them on the ladder since weapons better then this generally drop in very highlevel raid zones.<br><br>So, a group in need of a tank will choose a warrior if they are lacking in damage and either an sk or a warrior if they have a monk or rogue in group already. Some people prefer the sk alternative because of the much vaunted taunting ability but there it is. Rather then a group preferring a certain class always it depends on what the current composition of a group is like. On the other hand, a group without a puller might enlist the sk for this purpose instead of tanking. So you have two openings you can fill. There are actually three, I often group with several tanks and then I focus on protecting chanters and shamans instead of taking damage since the warrior simply isn't as good at that.<br><br>On to the changes. I could get used to the idea of placing more of the sk's damage in the spell department if VI made sure those spells were in line with our mana supply, meaning that the necro spells we get would have to cost significantly less for us then for the necros. As VI so far instead have added a mana penalty that decreases with levels but is always there I don't really see this happening. Why do the spells have to be cheaper? Well already I am severly chanter dependent if it comes to MT'ing in an exp group. Higher level necro spells at the same cost that necros cast them for would mean a VERY oom shadowknight in a very few pulls if without a chanter. Since exp groups are all about fast pulls and fast kills I would thereby be rendered inefficient as a tank if I had to cast spells for the same amount of mana as a necro. Performing the role of a snarer would leave us way behind on the wanted list in favor of a ranger since snaring can be very heavy on the mana. The ranger could deal his damage and do his snares while we would have to sacrifice damage in favor of keeping everything snared.<br><br>Also, all the damage spells that matter for an sk are dots. Personally i don't like dots in exp groups, there are too many things that can go wrong with them. I used to frequent The Hole alot since the exp down there simply outdid all other zones I'd been in and you had to deal with unmezzable golems that could add on you (on a personal note, I think they ruined the Hole in the recent patch to the zone. We went down to see what had changed and my chanter reported all golems as mezzable. It takes the challenge out of it and reduces the zones difficulty substantially in my opinion. They day I as a level 53 tank along with four of my friends all around 55 or so went down and payed Kindle a visit was one of the proudest in EQ so far. Others will now be denied that same sense of accomplishment). There are not many exp zones with the unmezzable factor but a named might start in on your group or an ae mob that needs to be dispatched might show up and the need for changing targets becomes obvious. The dot prevents this. <br><br>From my perspective the changes proposed would actually result in a less desirable shadowknight, a weaker version of the warrior relying so heavily on such a commonly resisted weapon as spells and the presence of an enchanter to be able to function as an MT for an exp group. Higher level mobs will often have a complete immunity to one or all lines of spells but we were talking exp groups here. A necromancer in the group would also disable your damage output by overwriting your dots. All this for the cleric to be able to take an extra 500 hp's with her CH...I simply don't see it. You could solo better for sure but that wasn't what the poster wanted, he wanted sk's more desirable in exp groups.<br><br>Onwards in the thread...the original poster mentions that sk's can tank very well in zones like Seb, Chardok, Velks etc (zones I refer to as exp zones). I don't understand that, that is what you wanted? As for tanking the really big mobs, Neptunis is of course absolutely right. Defensive is the one attribute that makes a warrior MT instead of an sk, simple as that. I have enough ac to be at the point where mobs hit me for the same amount as the warriors and don't trail them that much in hp. However, even with 6 or 7k hp's I would be a smear on the ground if I attempted to tank Lord Vyemm or anything like that. Hell, he rispostes on me for 1k dmg! Defensive is the divider between sk and warrior tanking ability as has already been mentioned here a couple of times by now.<br><br>I like the way sk's are. I like being MT on Hate raids (yes, the second floor also), part of the pull team and sometimes ST. Sk's need an intelligent player? Yes they do, not to time a lifetap so that you survive for the Ch to go through, that could be done by a properly conditioned monkey but to effortlessly switch between all of our different roles. <br>It takes being alert to know when to step in as ST and when the situation is in hand. It takes intelligence to figure out the game mechanics that allow you to pull mobs that would kill you in 3 seconds or to single difficult named mobs in a cluster of guards. It takes an analytic mind to figure out the different ways aggro can work for you and against you. I believe sk's have a &quot;bad&quot; reputation because of the fact that there are so many players not up to the challenge that fail when asked to fill one of these roles.<br><br>However, in one aspect the sk is lacking. We don't have a disc that could be strategically used in a raid environment. Warriors of course have their defensive and damage dealers have their offensive discs. All of them have a short reuse time and can therefore be figured into a fight. Someone suggested decreasing the reuse time on Leechcurse and to this I have to say &quot;please don't VI&quot;. The disc is as I have stated before completely useless, I've tried it in every situation imaginable where it could have benefitted my purpose but alas, it remains the disc I hit if I get jumped by a higher level green at low health. Fighting in a group I've used it once when we were in a tight spot to save the cleric the trouble of healing those two bubs also. It has no strategical value at all. Granted, if I'm on a cr mission and happen upon a green melee type mob I may use it to regain some health and then quickly fd to stay that way. My one wish would be that they made for something in the AA that could have a strategical application. Instead they gave us a horse. And more damn things on the HT timer. I will still be hitting Unholy Aura and HT and thereby using up both discs and HT when I have all of my aa abilities.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
