	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, from a damage dealing perspective, yeah, the higher INT characters might gain an edge--how much, Im not certain, but i wouldnt imagine it being too much.&nbsp;&nbsp;For instance, the same DoT isnt going to stack over &amp; over again, so it isnt like the SK is going to be blowing through their mana like no tomorrow.  Granted, the mana cost might be higher, but who wouldnt welcome a better spell anyways, regardless of mana (in general).<br><br>What you didnt mention, however, is that the ORG SK would gain a HUGE advantage in terms of being able to tank due to his higher STA.  SKs are tanks fellas, lets not forget that.  =)<br><br>Re: lvl 60 vs lvl 1.  I COMPLETELY agree with your assessment.  Far too often people find themselves concerned with what happens at the end rather than considering what is took to get there.  For instance, in the NFL, people seem to think that a bad call at the end of the game has far more reaching effects than they did say, in the 2nd quarter.  Nothing could be farther from the truth.  Every play has just as much importance to determine the outcome of a game--time holds no biases.<br><br>This, however, is somewhat different, as the journey to get to lvl 51 is FAR DIFFERENT than the journey getting from 51 to 60.  It probably takes most people more time to get to 60 from 51 than to get to 51 from 1.  Perhaps that is why most people focus on the higher levels than the lower ones.<br><br>Further, it just makes good sense; similar to business planning.  You are always budgeting for the future, always trying to guess &amp; project results &amp; courses of action.  That said, a character should do the same thing--ask yourself what you want to obtain, how you are going to get there, and what is needed to get there.  A great many people will say they want to hit lvl 60 &amp; plan accordingly.  It probably makes sense if you think about it   =)<br><br>Lunatic<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
